entry.title: Deprecate vector<v8::Local>, parts 1 and 2
entry.content:
According to V8's public API documentation, local handles (i.e.,

objects of type v8::Local) "should never be allocated on the heap".

This disallows heap-allocated data structures containing instances of

v8::Local, like std::vector>. It is unfortunate

that the V8 API itself requires the usage of such data structures.



This CL starts the deprecation of such data structures. It replaces

such vectors with v8::LocalVector, recently introduced in V8 API,

which behave exactly the same with the exception that the V8 isolate

must be passed upon construction.



Most of the changes in this CL are trivial and are related to renderer

extensions and accessibility features.



Among the non-trivial changes of this CL:



1. It adds the new vector type to the gin::Converter and renderer

V8 platform bindings conversion.

2. It specializes the gin::internal::ArgumentHolder template for

accepting such vectors.

entry.title: Add build flag for options.disclaim_responsibility in chromedriver
entry.content:
In chromedriver the options.disclaim_responsibility is set to true when

launching chrome binary to make Google's CI server happy, however for

some vender builds like Microsoft Teams they need to turn this off in

their test automation. We should make this option a build flag to make

both sides happy.



(In many CI enviroments, when the tested binary needs to request a macOS

permission suching as accessing camera/microphone, they usually grant

Terminal.app the necessary permissions so the built binaries can inherit

the permissions automatially. With options.disclaim_responsibility set

to true, macOS will ask permissions for the generated binary every time,

which essentially hangs the test automation.)

All InvalidationHandler instances are looking at the latest

invalidation per topic only in OnIncomingInvalidation. Handlers either

handle

topic in invalidator_registrar_with_memory.cc. In case of a handler

being interested in multiple topics, OnIncomingInvalidation might be

called multiple times in direct succession.



This reduces complexity in the handlers and opens up opportunities to

simplify caching and processing of incoming invalidations in

components/invalidation.

entry.title: snap-groups: Start overview in kFasterSplitScreenSetup
entry.content:
This consolidates showing partial overview to be behind the

kFasterSplitScreenSetup flag for dogfood in M120. When this is true,

snapping one window will start overview, but snapping the second

window will *not* form a snap group.



Due to `OverviewController::OnWindowActivating()` ending Overview, which

ends SplitViewOverviewSession and AutoSnapController, we need it to call

`AutoSnapController::OnWindowActivating()` directly. This is safe and

expected because Overview is expected to outlive

SplitViewOverviewSession, which owns AutoSnapController.



Note that AutoSnapController still needs to observe

`wm::ActivationChangeObserver::OnWindowActivated()` for tablet mode

and clamshell mode when IsFasterSplitScreenOrSnapGroupArm1 is *not*

enabled.



This currently only supports the first two snapped windows. A follow-

up CL will implement multiple partial overview sessions, i.e. on top

of two snapped windows.

> Files app: Enable TS checkJs in the tsconfig

>

> This changes the type-checking for JS files from Closure to TS.

>

> Convert the following externs to definitions:

> * VolumeInfo

>

> To import such definitions in JS files it has to be via JSDoc `import`

> since TS doesn't allow `import type` in JS files.

>

> Notable type changes in JSDocs:

> * `Object` becomes `Record`.

> * `function()` becomes `function():void`.

> * `import('../externs/volume_info.js').VolumeInfo` for type-only

> imports.

>

> For externs or things marked as `@interface`, TS doesn't allow empty

> methods if it contains a `@returns`, so I added return to appease TS.

entry.title: Add some {D}CHECKs to suss out crashes in AXObject::IsKeyboardFocusable
entry.content:
There have been crashes coming from AXObject::IsKeyboardFocusable()

where element->NeedsStyleRecalc() is false, but a lifecycle update

is forced by Element::IsKeyboardFocusable(). There's a slight

disconnect between checking NeedsStyleRecalc() and what the

UpdateStyleAndLayoutTreeForNode() function actually checks, which is

NeedsLayoutTreeUpdateForNodeIncludingDisplayLocked(). Either of those

can be true while the other is false.



This CL just adds a DCHECK that NeedsStyleRecalc() is false in

IsFocusableStyle(), which should verify that

IsFocusableStyleAfterUpdate() is not skipping things. It also adds

a CHECK in AXObject::IsKeyboardFocusable() that

NeedsLayoutTreeUpdateForNodeIncludingDisplayLocked() is false - if

that fails, it proves that AXObject is not always running

AXObject::IsKeyboardFocusable() with fully clean style *and* layout.

This CL also puts back the old CHECK that NeedsStyleRecalc() is

false, to ensure that (old) condition is still holding.



Patchsets 1-4 also contain other fairly random approaches to this

problem, but none convinced me that they would fix anything related

to this crash.

entry.title: [AppList] Fix positioning of close button when using search box
entry.content:
When activating the search box in tablet mode, the close button can

sometimes end up positioned incorrectly because the close button is

laid out next to the assistant button during the fade in/out

animations. To fix this, put the assistant button and the close+filter

buttons inside their own container views. These container views are then

parented by a fill layout manager view, so that the button containers

overlap are laid out on top of each other instead of side by side. This

makes it so that the button fade in/out animations overlap correctly.



Also, to simplify the fade in/out animations, animate the opacity of the

button containers instead of the buttons themselves. This also allows

button press events to pass to the correct button once the overlapping

containers are set to !visible after the fade out animations complete.



Finally increment pixel test revisions, and simplify some of the

numbering by skipping a revision for the case when IsJellyEnabled()

is false. Some revisions also had to be skipped because these pixel

tests were incremented previously but the change was reverted. This

simplification should make these revision changes easier to deal with

moving forward.

entry.title: Migrate security_interstitials to JS modules.
entry.content:
Security interstitials UIs are not proper WebUI pages and therefore they

can't load any dependencies at runtime, as there is no backing

WebUIDataSource to serve them.



For this reason, these UIs resort to bundling all the code to a single

JS and HTML file pair at buildtime. Currently this is achieved by using

Grit which is problematic because:

- It relies on Grit's obsolete flattenhtml=true mechanism

- It doesn't work with JS modules (Grit simply concatenates files)



Addressed here by leveraging the bundle_js() GN rule which is the

canonical way in the codebase for generating JS bundles from

modularized JS code.



This removes one of the last few non-JS module code in the codebase, and

paves the way for further migrating such files to TypeScript.

entry.title: Reland "frame: Flip fullscreen state on TabletModeToggled"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 8af6e204ac597d1be03269520a76258af57b6aea



There are two cases where fullscreen and immersive state differs:

1. Fullscreen is enabled but not Immersive

2. Imemrsive is enabled but not Fullscreen



The reverted cl only handled the case 1.

This CL also addresses the case 2 by checking whether fullscreen and

imemrsive should be enabled independently.



The case 1 is tested by LockedFullscreenBrowserNonClientChromeOSTest.

The case 2 is tested by HomeLauncherBrowserNonClienChromeOSTest.



Also Immerisve + Tablet behavior is tested by

- ToggleTabletModeWhileImmersiveModeEnabled

- ToggleImmersiveModeWhileTabletModeEnabled



More details: go/fullscreen-and-immersive-on-chromeos



Original change's description:

> frame: Flip fullscreen state on TabletModeToggled

>

> This CL fixes the behavior for both Ash and Lacros when entering tablet

> mode while immersive mode is enabled.

>

> Currently, immersive mode state is tied to fullscreen state since

> FullscreenController::ToggleBrowserFullscreenMode() eventually calls

> ImmersiveModeController::SetEnabled to align the state.

> However, OnTabletModeToggled only updates immersive mode state while

> it does not for fullscreen state. This causes the incorrect state

> where fullscreen is still enabled while tablet mode is enabled so

> that the tablet mode feature such as swiping down/up is unusable.

>

> Locked fullscreen is the only exception where immersive and fullscreen

> mode may have different states. In such case, both was_enabled and

> ShouldEnableImmersiveModeController() must be false, so it won't break

> the locked fullscreen state. This behavior is verified by

> LockedFullscreenBrowserNonClientFrameViewChromeOSTest.ToggleTabletMode

>

> This CL lets FullscreenController toggles fullscreen mode instead of

> only updating immersive mode.

>

folder, leftovers from previous builds, which in turn would cause flaky

many bundled files were actually generated.

semantincs.

entry.title: [SurfacePolish] Simplify search bar coloring state and flow.
entry.content:
This is a refactoring CL without functionality change.



Fixing sticky search bar icon colors for surface polish requires getting

LocationBarMediator to assign button tints depending on "isColorful",

i.e., the state to indicate whether hint text and icons are colorful

(instead of being plain). This CL refactors code ahead of the change to

address the following:

1. LocationBarMediator cannot read "isColorful" directly, and did not

store it (previously it was set on use). However, icon tints are

updated in onPrimaryColorChanged(), and so the state will need to be

available.

2. UrlBarMediator.setUrlBarHintTextColorForSurfacePolish() takes

|usePreviousHintTextColor| as decision variable to choose between two

disjoint code paths, leading to entanglement with extra params.

3. ToolbarPhone.updateLocationBarForSurfacePolish()'s UI update logic

is "update-on-change" in disguise, and can be simplified.



Changes to address the above:

1. Get LocationBarMediator to store "isColorful", + more:

* To store "isColorful" state:

* Add|mIsSurfacePolishOmniboxColorEnabled|.

* Add setter setIsSurfacePolishOmniboxColorEnabled(). This is naive

and does not trigger update.

* Update ToolBarPhone.setLocationBarCoordinator() to set the

flag state for |mIsSurfacePolishOmniboxColorEnabled|.

* Remove updateAssistantVoiceSearchDrawableAndColors():

* For separation of concerns: Move |mLocationBarLayout| drawable

initialization to onFinishNativeInitialization().

* Remove updateLensButtonColors() (coalesced to below).

* Add updateButtonTints() to update mic and lens button tints.

* Made public in anticipation of usage.



2. Split default vs. colorful hint text color assignment path.

* UrlBarMediator: Split setUrlBarHintTextColorForSurfacePolish() into:

setUrlBarHintTextColorForDefault()

setUrlBarHintTextColorForSurfacePolish()

for |usePreviousHintTextColor| taking false / true.

* LocationBarMediator: Replace

setUrlBarHintTextColorForSurfacePolish()

with setUrlBarHintTextColor(), dispatching to the above call

depending on decision variable; pass store "isColorful".



3. ToolBarPhone:

* Replace|mHasSetLocationBarStyling| with

|mIsStartOrNtpWithSurfacePolish| for the "isColorful".

* updateLocationBarForSurfacePolish():

* Directly update |mHasSetLocationBarStyling|

* explicitly detect changes to trigger UI update.



Also update wrappers in UrlBarCoordinators (-1, +2 functions) and

LocationBarCoordinator (-1, +3 functions).

entry.title: Pass --disable-field-trial-config to tests that need it.
entry.content:
Affected tests already run without the testing config applied,

so this CL makes it explicit.



Context: Browser tests that use ScopedFeatureList and pass

params presently cause the field trial testing config to be

entirely disabled. (details: crbug.com/1491463#c8)

We plan to fix this, but some existing tests rely on this

(fail with the testing config). This CL annotates those

tests explicitly by making them specify the flag for that.



Once all the CLs updating such tests land (sharded via git

cl split), the following CL to make ScopedFeatureList not

disable the testing config can land:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4935093



As many tests are affected, it will be up to their owners

to do any necessary follow up if the tests should be made to

pass with the testing config (per the comments this CL adds).



Note: I did a best effort to have the new flag only apply to the

subset of tests that needed it when it was a single or a small

number of tests that were affected, by introducing subclasses

for the affected tests. In other cases, where lots of tests in

the same file fail, the flag is added to the original test class.



Note: The --disable-field-trial-config flag is passed simply

by name intentionally, to avoid additional complexity from

depending on components/variations and includes to reference

the existing constant for it. The name is unlikely to change and

this way, we need less complex code to add this to the tests.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.
